    <!-- Chunk 3: Getting started -->
    <section>
      <h2>How do I get started with SQL Query Lab?</h2>
      <p>
        Open <a href="https://learn-sql-practice.vercel.app">https://learn-sql-practice.vercel.app</a> — the app loads immediately with a hospital database pre-selected. Click <strong>Run</strong> (or press <kbd>Cmd/Ctrl + Enter</kbd>) to execute the query in the editor. To start a practice question, click <strong>All Questions</strong> in the top bar and browse by category (SELECT, JOIN, aggregation, subqueries, DML) or difficulty (easy, medium, hard). Your progress saves automatically to browser localStorage. The sandbox database state also persists between sessions, so your work survives browser restarts.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Chunk 4: Databases -->
    <section>
      <h2>What databases can I practice with in SQL Query Lab?</h2>
      <p>
        SQL Query Lab ships with three pre-seeded SQLite databases containing realistic relational data. The <strong>hospital</strong> database includes patients, doctors, appointments, and billing tables — useful for practicing aggregation, JOINs across multiple tables, and date-based filtering. The <strong>company</strong> database covers employees, departments, projects, and salaries — ideal for GROUP BY, HAVING, and window function practice. The <strong>school</strong> database includes students, courses, enrollments, and grades — covering self-joins and subquery patterns. Switch between databases using the dropdown in the top bar. All databases are restored to their original seed state by clicking <strong>Reset DB</strong>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Chunk 5: MS SQL / T-SQL -->
    <section>
      <h2>Can I practice MS SQL Server T-SQL syntax in SQL Query Lab?</h2>
      <p>
        Yes, via two pathways. The <strong>MS SQL mode</strong> (third button in the mode toggle) translates any SQLite SQL you write into equivalent T-SQL — handling type name conversions (INTEGER → INT, TEXT → NVARCHAR, REAL → FLOAT), function replacements (LIKE → CHARINDEX or PATINDEX for pattern matching), LIMIT/OFFSET pagination (converts to FETCH NEXT / OFFSET), and SET operations differences. For live practice against an actual SQL Server instance, use <strong>Live mode</strong> — connect to your MS SQL Server using Windows Authentication or SQL Authentication. The connection credentials are encrypted server-side before storage. Live mode supports executing queries, viewing execution plans, and browsing the object explorer.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Chunk 6: Interview prep -->
    <section>
      <h2>Is SQL Query Lab good for SQL interview preparation?</h2>
      <p>
        Yes. SQL Query Lab's practice mode is specifically designed around the question patterns that appear in technical interviews: multi-table JOINs, GROUP BY with HAVING, correlated subqueries, EXISTS vs IN, CTEs, and row-number window functions. The 74 questions cover the most common interview SQL scenarios across the hospital and company databases. Each question shows the expected result set, so you can self-verify without needing a reference answer. The comparison view (Your Output vs Expected) highlights exact cell-level mismatches. For whiteboard-style preparation, the MS SQL translation feature helps you practice translating concepts to T-SQL, which is the dialect used in most enterprise environments running Microsoft SQL Server.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Chunk 7: Author/Trust section -->
    <section class="author-section">
      <h2>About SQL Query Lab — who built this and why</h2>
      <p>
        SQL Query Lab was built as a practical learning tool for developers and database professionals who need to practice SQL without fighting environment setup. The project was first deployed in 2024 and has been actively maintained with regular updates to its question bank and feature set. The frontend runs as a static site deployed on Vercel with zero runtime server — sql.js executes SQL in the browser using WebAssembly. The backend (for live SQL Server connections) runs as a containerized Node.js service on DigitalOcean. Connection credentials are encrypted using AES-256-GCM with a server-side master password before being stored in SQLite. Last reviewed and updated May 2026. Questions, feedback, and feature requests are welcome via the project's GitHub repository.
      </p>
    </section>

